The Nigerian stocks suffered another week of losses as worries deepened about the impact of the novel Coronavirus (Covid-19) outbreak and as oil prices fell to 17-year lows during the week. The All-Share Index (ASI) fell 534.92 points or 2.35 per cent week-on-week (W-O-W) to settle at 22,198.43. Thus, investors lost N279 billion as market capitalisation declined to N11.568 trillion. Despite the decline, sector performance was bullish. Insurance index led the gainers by 2.80 per cent, due to improved demand in NEM Insurance and Cornerstone Insurance. Similarly, the Banking and Oil & Gas indices advanced 0.29 per cent and 0.22 per cent respectively, following price appreciation in Union Bank of Nigeria (UBN), Wema Bank and Eterna. Conversely, the Industrial and Consumer Goods indices fell 4.85 per cent and 3.20 per cent on the back of price depreciation in Lafarge Africa and Dangote Cement as well as Nestle Nigeria and Flour Mills of Nigeria. Market breadth for the week was positive as 35 equities appreciated in price, 27 equities depreciated in price, while 101 equities remained unchanged. Cadbury Nigeria led the gainers table by 26.26 per cent to close at N6.25, per share. NPF Microfinance Bank followed with a gain of 23.53 per cent to close at N1.05, while United Capital went up by 11.11 per cent to close to 90 kobo, per share. On the other side, Wapic Insurance led the decliners table by 22.22 per cent to close at 21 kobo, per share. United Bank for Africa (UBA) followed with a loss of 18.70 per cent to close at N5.00 and May & Baker Nigeria declined by 16.74 per cent to close at N1.79, per share. Overall, a  total turnover of 2.804 billion shares worth N32.559 billion in 31,715 deals were traded last week by investors on the floor of the Exchange, in contrast to a total of 3.964 billion shares valued at N43.703 billion that exchanged hands previous week in 26,054 deals. In the new week, analysts at Cowry Asset Management Limited expected the local bourse to close in red amid negative impact of Covid-19 pandemic. Notwithstanding, we expect investors to take advantage of the lower share prices as possible further decline in crude oil prices could further depress share prices. Analysts at Afrinvest Limited also expected the bearish trend to persist in the absence of any major market catalyst to stimulate investors’ appetite towards the equities market.